Start the Virtual Machine
Open Oracle VM VirtualBox.
Select the VM you created (for example Ubuntu or another Linux VM).
Click Start.
Log in to the Linux system.
2️⃣ Open Terminal

In Linux:

Press Ctrl + Alt + T, or
Go to Applications → Terminal

Terminal will open for running commands.

3️⃣ Install C Compiler (GCC)

Most Linux systems use the GNU Compiler Collection (GCC) for compiling C programs.

Update package list
sudo apt update
Install GCC
sudo apt install build-essential

This installs:

GCC compiler
G++ compiler
Libraries
Development tools
4️⃣ Verify Installation

Check whether the compiler is installed.

gcc --version

You should see GCC version details.

Example:

gcc (Ubuntu 11.4.0) 11.4.0
5️⃣ Create a Simple C Program

Create a file called hello.c

nano hello.c

Write the following code:

#include <stdio.h>

int main() {
    printf("Hello World\n");
    return 0;
}

Save the file:

Press
Ctrl + X → Y → Enter

6️⃣ Compile the Program

Use the gcc compiler:

gcc hello.c -o hello

Explanation:

hello.c → source file
-o hello → output executable file
7️⃣ Run the Program

Execute the compiled program:

./hello

Output:

Hello World
8️⃣ Example Program (Addition)

Create another file:

nano add.c

Program:

#include <stdio.h>

int main() {
    int a,b,sum;
    printf("Enter two numbers: ");
    scanf("%d %d",&a,&b);
    sum = a + b;
    printf("Sum = %d",sum);
    return 0;
}

Compile:

gcc add.c -o add

Run:

./add

Example output:

Enter two numbers: 5 7
Sum = 12
9️⃣ Summary of Commands
Command	Purpose
sudo apt update	update package list
sudo apt install build-essential	install GCC compiler
gcc program.c -o program	compile C program
./program	run compiled program